ally considering Scala's behavior. It seems that Java's anonymous classes might not be public.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying Method Access in Java**\\n\\nI need to ensure the method name is declared in a public superclass. The `getAccessibleMethodFromSuperclass` needs the parent class to be public, and I can check the method via `parentClass.getMethod(methodName, paramTypes)`. It looks like using a package-private subclass of a public superclass might work, but I wonder if the `Method` object’s declaring class can still be non-public. I'm curious if the method `toString` from `java.util.Collections.unmodifiableSet` is inherited, as it could return the public `Object.toString` if it's not overridden.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering access modifiers**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how even if a class is private, I can still have a public method. Specifically, with `MemberUtils.isAccessible` being true, should I have a top-level public test class? Maybe a Scala class could be public to allow that? Alright, I guess I need to make some edits here. It’s interesting how access modifiers can influence my design choices! I'll have to figure out the best approach.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_3oHkc4GPDSSx609teYDQSaFc|fc_03a0e1975ef686520169fd670ff34881978884e91685dd64cd", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.playframework/play_3/3.0.0/src/test/scala/org_playframework/play_3/MethodUtilsTest.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "class MethodUtilsTest {\n  @Test", "newText": "class MethodUtilsTest {\n  private class MethodUtilsPackagePrivateGreeting extends MethodUtilsPublicGreeting {\n    override def greet(name: String): String = s\"hello $name\"\n  }\n\n  private class MethodUtilsPackagePrivateOverride extends MethodUtilsPublicBase {\n    override def inheritedEcho(value: String): String = s\"child:$value\"\n  }\n\n  @Test"}, {"oldText": "private class MethodUtilsPackagePrivateGreeting extends MethodUtilsPublicGree